<DOC><DOCNO> AP880414-0132 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-88 1411EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-BRF--WeatherWire     04-14 0133</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Weather Wire,120</SECOND><HEAD>Virginia Firm Wins Weather Wire Contract</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Contel ASC of McLean, Va., has been chosen tomodernize the national weather wire, the National Weather Serviceannounced on Thursday.   The cost to upgrade the national weather information and warningsystem is expected to be about $12 million, the National Oceanicand Atmospheric Administration reported.   The weather wire currently operates on a system of low-speed,land based Teletype circuits. It will be replaced by a satellitesystem broadcasting directly to subscribers, the agency reported.   The changeover is expected to begin operation in October, withfull operation for the National Weather Service completed in a year.   The new system will deliver information at a rate 16 timesfaster than the current system, according to Weather Servicedirector Elbert W. Friday.</TEXT></DOC>